”中，苹果公司一直保持着令人怀疑的沉默，直到现在。 <a data-i13n="cpos:1;pos:1" href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-07-19/apple-preps-ajax-generative-ai-apple-gpt-to-rival-openai-and-google?sref=10lNAhZ9">据<em>彭博社最初报道，该公司正在创建自己的聊天机器人。</em></a>工程师们厚颜无耻地将工具集命名为“AppleGPT”，但它实际上被称为 Ajax，因为大型语言模型 (LLM) 是使用 Google 的 JAX 框架构建的。消息人士称，苹果有多个团队致力于该项目，其中一个团队致力于解决潜在的隐私问题。</p><p>苹果实际上会用这个机器人做什么？目前尚不清楚，因为该公司似乎没有关于用例场景、发布日期或平台的任何可靠计划。一位不愿透露姓名的消息人士告诉<em>彭博社</em>，预计明年将发布正式公告以及更多细节。苹果公司下个月还将举行年度财报电话会议，这可能会对 Ajax 的情况产生一些影响。</p><span id="end-legacy-contents"></span><p>在此之前，苹果首席执行官蒂姆·库克向<a data-i13n="cpos:2;pos:1" href="https://www.goodmorningamerica.com/News/video/tim-cook-apple-vision-pro-change-people-engage-99863168"><em>《早安美国》</em></a>表示，公司正在“密切关注”生成式人工智能。据<em>彭博社报道</em>，John Giannandrea 和苹果软件工程高级副总裁 Craig Federighi 正在领导该计划。 Giannandrea 最初受聘来监督 Siri 及其机器学习功能，所以也许这个陷入困境的数字助理将会变得更加有用。</p><p>近几个月来，生成式人工智能领域呈爆炸式增长，几乎所有大型科技公司都加入了炒作行列。就在昨天， <a data-i13n="cpos:3;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/meta-and-microsoft-release-llama-2-an-ai-language-model-for-commercial-use-163615807.html">Meta 和微软发布了 Llama 2，</a>这是一款用于商业用途的人工智能聊天机器人。</p>本文最初发表在 Engadget 上：https://www.engadget.com/apple-is-reportedly-developing-its-own-generative-ai-chatbot-to-rival-chatgpt-174507671.html?src=rss]]>; </description><link/><![CDATA[https://www.engadget.com/apple-is-reportedly-developing-its-own-generative-ai-chatbot-to-rival-chatgpt-174507671.html?src=rss]]><source_id> engadget_479</source_id><guid ispermalink="false"> ba2d437c-e938-40d8-bb85-8765cd7df656</guid><dc:creator>劳伦斯·邦克</dc:creator><source/><![CDATA[Engadget]]><dc:publisher>恩杰特</dc:publisher><dc:rightsholder>恩杰特</dc:rightsholder><pubDate>Wed, 19 Jul 2023 17:45:07 +0000</pubDate><ingested> 1689788757</ingested><modified> 2023-07-19T17:46:00+00:00 </modified><category><![CDATA[Technology & Electronics]]></category><category><![CDATA[site|engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[provider_name|Engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[region|US]]></category><category><![CDATA[language|en-US]]></category><category><![CDATA[author_name|Lawrence Bonk]]></category><media:content height="3781" medium="image" url="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-07/80d842c0-265b-11ee-9ab8-ccd20ac66b4e" width="5672"><media:keywords>标题</media:keywords><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[1]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[ ]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[ ]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[ ]]></media:title></media:content><media:content height="3781" medium="image" url="https://media-mbst-pub-ue1.s3.amazonaws.com/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-07/80d842c0-265b-11ee-9ab8-ccd20ac66b4e" width="5672"><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[2]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[ASSOCIATED PRESS]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[FILE - An Apple logo adorns the facade of the downtown Brooklyn Apple store on March 14, 2020, in New York. Apple became the first publicly traded company to close a trading day with a $3 trillion market value, marking another milestone for a technology juggernaut that has reshaped society with a line-up of products that churn out eye-popping profits. (AP Photo/Kathy Willens, File)]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[Apple $3 Trillion]]></media:title></media:content></item><item><title><![CDATA[Instagram beats copyright infringement lawsuit involving embedded photos]]></title><description type="html"><![CDATA[<p> <a data-i13n="cpos:1;pos:1" href="https://gizmodo.com/instagram-wins-copyright-claims-case-on-embedded-photos-1850651894"><ins>据</ins><em><ins>Gizmodo 报道，美国第九巡回上诉法院的三名法官组成的陪审团做出了有利于 Meta 旗下 Instagram 的裁决，此前两名摄影师指控这家社交媒体巨头侵犯版权。</ins></em></a>该案的基本要点是，Instagram 在未经内容创作者明确同意的情况下允许外部网站和出版物嵌入图像，从而侵犯了版权。</p><p>该案可以追溯到2016年，当时<em>《时代》</em>杂志在未经许可的情况下嵌入了摄影师马修·布劳尔(Matthew Brauer)拍摄的希拉里·克林顿(Hillary Clinton)的Instagram照片。 2020 年， <em>Buzzfeed</em>对亚历克西斯·亨利 (Alexis Hunley) 拍摄的“黑人生命也是命”抗议活动的照片做了同样的事情。这对照片起诉 Instagram，声称该社交媒体公司从未要求第三方获得嵌入受版权保护的照片或视频的许可，从而导致他们面临二次侵权指控。</p><span id="end-legacy-contents"></span><p>该诉讼最初于 2021 年在加利福尼亚州提起，但法官驳回了诉讼，理由是相关新闻媒体没有存储原始图像，甚至没有显示其副本。相反，它只是将 Instagram 上已有的内容显示为嵌入内容。两人对这一决定提出上诉，但现已在联邦法院失败。其推理<a data-i13n="elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Scribd;elmt:;cpos:2;pos:1" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=cc8a75f0-b695-4a6a-a33c-41019f4bfaa4&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Scribd&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAY-0x8M71cUg3wGZPv38IvH_ntW1D1PBqknCl5tPNUFI&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.scribd.com%2Fdocument%2F659785820%2FHunley-Brauer-Instagram-Appeal" class="rapid-with-clickid"><ins>与加州的判决相同，</ins></a>法官们一致认为，嵌入照片或视频时，不会复制底层内容。</p><p>然而，值得注意的是，联邦法官小组确实表示，亨利和布劳尔对版权所有者实际控制并最终从其作品中获利的能力提出了“严重且经过充分论证”的政策担忧。 Instagram has also addressed the issue in convening years, adding an option in 2021 that allows users to make images unembeddable. This change came after the platform was lobbied by the American Society of Media Photographers (ASMP) and the National Press Photographers Association (NPPA).</p><p> This may not be the end of the case, as <a data-i13n="cpos:3;pos:1" href="https://www.reuters.com/legal/transactional/column-instagram-dodges-photographers-copyright-claims-appeal-case-likely-2023-07-18/"><em><ins>Reuters</ins></em> <ins>reports</ins></a> that the photographers can petition for a rehearing with a panel of 11 randomly-selected judges, though Brauer and Hunley haven&#39;t addressed this course of action.</p><p> There&#39;s also the underlying meaning of this court decision. All by itself, the ruling indicates that third parties, such as media publications, can embed photos and videos at will without ever asking the original content creator for permission. However, related cases have been popping up with differing outcomes, setting the stage for a higher-court showdown at some point.</p><p> For instance, a New York judge handed down a <a data-i13n="cpos:4;pos:1" href="https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/business/business-news/judge-rules-news-publishers-violated-copyright-by-embedding-tweets-tom-brady-photo-1085342/"><ins>somewhat contradictory ruling</ins></a> back in 2018 when a photographer sued various publications after they embedded tweets with an original image of NFL legend Tom Brady. The judge sided with the photographer here, stating in her decision that “the fact that the image was hosted on a server owned and operated by an unrelated third party does not shield them from this result,” adding “nowhere does the Copyright Act suggest that possession of an image is necessary in order to display it. Indeed, the purpose and language of the Act support the opposite view.”</p> This article originally appeared on Engadget at https://www.engadget.com/instagram-beats-copyright-infringement-lawsuit-involving-embedded-photos-170547770.html?src=rss]]>; </description><link/><![CDATA[https://www.engadget.com/instagram-beats-copyright-infringement-lawsuit-involving-embedded-photos-170547770.html?src=rss]]><source_id> engadget_479</source_id><guid ispermalink="false"> 2577faf4-65f1-4d18-8b31-cd579abe6dab</guid><dc:creator> Lawrence Bonk</dc:creator><source/><![CDATA[Engadget]]><dc:publisher> Engadget</dc:publisher><dc:rightsholder> Engadget</dc:rightsholder><pubDate> Wed, 19 Jul 2023 17:05:47 +0000</pubDate><ingested> 1689786349</ingested><modified> 2023-07-19T17:05:59+00:00 </modified><category><![CDATA[Company Legal & Law Matters]]></category><category><![CDATA[site|engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[provider_name|Engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[region|US]]></category><category><![CDATA[language|en-US]]></category><category><![CDATA[author_name|Lawrence Bonk]]></category><media:content height="3210" medium="image" url="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-07/5e70e440-2650-11ee-9f3d-eca4e21bccd1" width="4918"><media:keywords>标题</media:keywords><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><!